04957nam a22008655i 9780520341098DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203410987 a10.1525/97805203410982doi  a(DE-B1597)543525  a(OCoLC)1153453577  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBH201b.H29 1995 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a111/.852201 aHarrison, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10a1910 :bThe Emancipation of Dissonance /cThomas Harrison.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b1 frontisp., 25 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. The Emancipation of Dissonance -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Deficiency of Being -- tCHAPTER THREE. The Hole Called the Soul -- tCHAPTER FOUR. An Ethics of Misunderstanding -- tAfterword and Aftermath -- tPrimary Sources -- tSecondary Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe year 1910 marks an astonishing, and largely unrecognized, juncture in Western history. In this perceptive interdisciplinary analysis, Thomas Harrison addresses the extraordinary intellectual achievement of the time. Focusing on the cultural climate of Middle Europe and paying particular attention to the life and work of Carlo Michelstaedter, he deftly portrays the reciprocal implications of different discourses—philosophy, literature, sociology, music, and painting. His beautifully balanced and deeply informed study provides a new, wider, and more ambitious definition of expressionism and shows the significance of this movement in shaping the artistic and intellectual mood of the age.1910 probes the recurrent themes and obsessions in the work of intellectuals as diverse as Egon Schiele, Georg Trakl, Vasily Kandinsky, Georg Lukàcs, Georg Simmel, Dino Campana, and Arnold Schoenberg. Together with Michelstaedter, who committed suicide in 1910 at the age of 23, these thinkers shared the essential concerns of expressionism: a sense of irresolvable conflict in human existence, the philosophical status of death, and a quest for the nature of human subjectivity. Expressionism, Harrison argues provocatively, was a last, desperate attempt by the intelligentsia to defend some of the most venerable assumptions of European culture. This ideological desperation, he claims, was more than a spiritual prelude to World War I: it was an unheeded, prophetic critique.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAesthetics, Moderny20th century. 0aAnxiety. 0aExpressionism. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  a20th century europe.  a20th century history.  aacademic textbooks.  acarlo michelstaedter biographies.  adevelopment of science.  aeuropean anthropology.  aeuropean cultural climate.  aeuropean culture.  aeuropean history textbooks.  aeuropean history.  aeuropean literature.  aeuropean philosophy.  aeuropean science.  aevolution of science.  ahistory of carlo michelstaedter.  ahomeschool history textbooks.  ahuman sciences.  alearning from experts.  aphilosophy textbooks.  apostwar history.  astudy of culture.  aworld war i history.  ayear 1910.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020043240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520341098?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520341098423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520341098/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of Califor